{
  "executive_summary": "Integration architecture for a logistics platform connecting three external systems (SAP ERP via SFTP/XML, DHL Carrier API via REST/webhooks, and a Kafka-based Analytics Platform) using an event-driven backbone with dedicated Anti-Corruption Layers per external system. The design isolates each integration behind clear boundaries, ensures the 500ms webhook SLA via async processing, and provides a single internal event stream that feeds all downstream consumers including the analytics platform.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Internal Event Bus",
        "responsibility": "Central backbone for all domain events (OrderPlaced, OrderConfirmed, ShipmentCreated, DeliveryAttempted, DeliveryCompleted, DeliveryFailed). Single source of truth for event flow within the platform.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the canonical event schema. All internal components publish and subscribe here. No external system touches this directly."
      },
      {
        "name": "SAP Integration Adapter (ACL)",
        "responsibility": "Subscribes to OrderConfirmed events on the internal bus, transforms them to SAP-compatible XML, batches them, and deposits files on the SFTP endpoint every 15 minutes. Handles retry, idempotency (deduplication by order ID), and file naming conventions.",
        "boundaries": "Owns SAP XML schema mapping and SFTP connection lifecycle. Knows nothing about DHL or Analytics. Operates on a scheduled cadence (cron/timer), not event-driven push."
      },
      {
        "name": "DHL Integration Adapter (ACL)",
        "responsibility": "Outbound: translates ShipmentCreated events into DHL REST API calls to create shipments. Inbound: exposes a lightweight webhook endpoint that receives DHL status callbacks, translates them into internal domain events (DeliveryAttempted, DeliveryCompleted, DeliveryFailed), and publishes to the internal event bus.",
        "boundaries": "Owns DHL API client, authentication, rate limiting, and webhook signature verification. The webhook handler must respond within 500ms — it persists the raw payload and ACKs immediately, then processes asynchronously."
      },
      {
        "name": "Analytics Stream Publisher",
        "responsibility": "Subscribes to ALL domain events on the internal event bus and publishes them to the external Kafka topic in the schema required by the Analytics Platform. Handles schema evolution (Avro/JSON Schema with a schema registry).",
        "boundaries": "Owns the Kafka producer and the external analytics event schema. Read-only consumer of internal events — never mutates state."
      },
      {
        "name": "Webhook Ingress Gateway",
        "responsibility": "Thin HTTP layer that receives DHL webhook callbacks, validates signatures, persists the raw payload to a durable queue (or internal Kafka topic), and returns 200 OK immediately. Decouples HTTP response time from processing time to guarantee the 500ms SLA.",
        "boundaries": "Owns only HTTP concerns: TLS termination, signature validation, idempotency keys. Delegates all business logic to the DHL Integration Adapter consuming from the durable queue."
      },
      {
        "name": "Order Domain Service",
        "responsibility": "Core domain logic for order lifecycle. Emits OrderPlaced and OrderConfirmed events. Validates business invariants before state transitions.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the Order aggregate. Publishes events to the internal event bus. Has no knowledge of any external system."
      },
      {
        "name": "Shipment Domain Service",
        "responsibility": "Core domain logic for shipment lifecycle. Emits ShipmentCreated, DeliveryAttempted, DeliveryCompleted, DeliveryFailed events.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the Shipment aggregate. Consumes OrderConfirmed to trigger shipment creation workflows."
      },
      {
        "name": "Dead Letter & Retry Handler",
        "responsibility": "Captures failed integration attempts (SFTP upload failures, DHL API errors, Kafka publish failures) into a dead-letter store with exponential backoff retry. Provides observability dashboard and alerting.",
        "boundaries": "Cross-cutting concern. Each adapter routes failures here. Does not interpret business content — only handles delivery mechanics."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Order Domain Service",
        "to": "Internal Event Bus",
        "contract": "Publishes OrderPlaced{orderId, timestamp, lineItems, customer} and OrderConfirmed{orderId, timestamp, confirmedBy}",
        "coupling_type": "event (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Shipment Domain Service",
        "to": "Internal Event Bus",
        "contract": "Publishes ShipmentCreated{shipmentId, orderId, carrier, trackingNumber}, DeliveryAttempted{shipmentId, attemptTimestamp, result}, DeliveryCompleted{shipmentId, completedAt, signature}, DeliveryFailed{shipmentId, failureReason, attemptCount}",
        "coupling_type": "event (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Internal Event Bus",
        "to": "SAP Integration Adapter",
        "contract": "Subscribes to OrderConfirmed events. Adapter accumulates and flushes to SFTP on 15-minute schedule.",
        "coupling_type": "event (loose) + scheduled batch"
      },
      {
        "from": "SAP Integration Adapter",
        "to": "System A (SAP ERP)",
        "contract": "XML files deposited via SFTP. File naming: orders_{timestamp}_{batchId}.xml. SAP's proprietary IDoc or BAPI-compatible XML schema.",
        "coupling_type": "file-based integration (decoupled)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Internal Event Bus",
        "to": "DHL Integration Adapter",
        "contract": "Subscribes to ShipmentCreated to trigger outbound DHL API calls.",
        "coupling_type": "event (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "DHL Integration Adapter",
        "to": "System B (DHL Carrier API)",
        "contract": "REST POST to create shipment, REST GET for status polling (fallback). OAuth2 or API key auth. Respects DHL rate limits.",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous REST (tight, isolated behind ACL)"
      },
      {
        "from": "System B (DHL Carrier API)",
        "to": "Webhook Ingress Gateway",
        "contract": "HTTP POST with DHL status payload. HMAC signature header for verification. Must return 2xx within 500ms.",
        "coupling_type": "webhook callback (inbound async)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Webhook Ingress Gateway",
        "to": "DHL Integration Adapter",
        "contract": "Raw DHL payload placed on durable queue with metadata (receivedAt, idempotencyKey, rawBody).",
        "coupling_type": "async queue (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "DHL Integration Adapter",
        "to": "Internal Event Bus",
        "contract": "Translates DHL status into DeliveryAttempted, DeliveryCompleted, or DeliveryFailed and publishes.",
        "coupling_type": "event (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Internal Event Bus",
        "to": "Analytics Stream Publisher",
        "contract": "Subscribes to ALL six domain event types.",
        "coupling_type": "event (loose)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Analytics Stream Publisher",
        "to": "System C (Analytics Kafka)",
        "contract": "Produces to Kafka topic 'logistics.events' with Avro-encoded payloads. Keyed by orderId for partition ordering.",
        "coupling_type": "async stream (loose)"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1. OrderPlaced → OrderConfirmed emitted by Order Domain Service to Internal Event Bus. 2. OrderConfirmed is consumed by: (a) SAP Adapter — buffers and flushes XML to SFTP every 15 min, (b) Shipment Domain Service — creates shipment, emits ShipmentCreated. 3. ShipmentCreated consumed by DHL Adapter — calls DHL REST API to register shipment. 4. DHL sends webhook callbacks → Webhook Ingress Gateway ACKs <500ms, queues payload → DHL Adapter translates to DeliveryAttempted/Completed/Failed → publishes to Internal Event Bus. 5. Analytics Stream Publisher subscribes to ALL events on the Internal Event Bus and produces them to Kafka for System C in real-time. Dead Letter Handler captures failures at every integration boundary.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Anti-Corruption Layer (ACL)",
        "rationale": "Each external system has its own data model and protocol (XML/SFTP, REST/webhook, Kafka/Avro). ACLs isolate translation logic so the core domain never conforms to external schemas. If DHL changes their API, only the DHL ACL changes."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Event-Driven Architecture with Internal Event Bus",
        "rationale": "The six domain events are the natural integration backbone. Publishing them once to an internal bus allows N consumers (SAP, DHL, Analytics, future systems) without the domain services knowing about any of them. Classic fan-out."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Async Webhook Ingestion (Store-and-Forward)",
        "rationale": "The 500ms SLA on DHL webhook responses is a hard constraint. The Webhook Ingress Gateway stores the raw payload to a durable queue and ACKs immediately, decoupling HTTP response latency from processing complexity. This is the only pattern that reliably guarantees the SLA."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Outbox Pattern (for SAP batch)",
        "rationale": "OrderConfirmed events are stored in an outbox table. The SAP Adapter reads the outbox on a 15-minute schedule, transforms to XML, and uploads via SFTP. This ensures exactly-once delivery semantics — no events lost between emission and batch pickup, even if the adapter was down."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Dead Letter Queue with Exponential Backoff",
        "rationale": "Three different external systems with three different failure modes. Unified retry infrastructure avoids per-adapter retry logic duplication and provides a single pane of glass for operational visibility into integration health."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Gateway / Edge Service (Webhook Ingress)",
        "rationale": "Separating the HTTP ingress from the DHL Adapter allows independent scaling of the webhook receiver (which must be fast) from the translation logic (which must be correct). Also centralizes security concerns like signature verification."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Order Management",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Order (root: orderId, states: placed → confirmed → fulfilled)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Shipment Management",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["Shipment (root: shipmentId, linked to orderId, states: created → in_transit → delivered | failed)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "ERP Integration (SAP)",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["OutboxBatch (root: batchId, contains list of confirmed order references, states: pending → exported → acknowledged)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Carrier Integration (DHL)",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["CarrierShipment (root: carrierTrackingId, maps to internal shipmentId, tracks external status)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Event Streaming (Analytics)",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["StreamPosition (root: consumerId, tracks last-published offset for exactly-once semantics)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "Shipment Management",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Order Management publishes OrderConfirmed, Shipment Management consumes it to trigger shipment creation. Order owns the contract."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management",
        "downstream": "ERP Integration (SAP)",
        "relationship": "Conformist with ACL — SAP Adapter conforms to SAP's XML schema via an Anti-Corruption Layer. The internal Order model is never polluted by SAP's structure."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Shipment Management",
        "downstream": "Carrier Integration (DHL)",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier with ACL — DHL Adapter translates between internal shipment model and DHL's REST/webhook model. DHL dictates their API schema; the ACL prevents it from leaking inward."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Order Management + Shipment Management",
        "downstream": "Event Streaming (Analytics)",
        "relationship": "Published Language — all six domain events form a published language consumed by the Analytics Stream Publisher and projected to Kafka."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Internal event bus as the single integration backbone rather than point-to-point adapters",
      "gains": "Loose coupling, easy to add new consumers, single event contract, natural audit trail",
      "sacrifices": "Additional infrastructure (message broker), eventual consistency between systems, more complex debugging of event chains",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Point-to-point integration (simpler but O(n²) coupling)", "Shared database integration (tight coupling, schema lock-in)", "ESB / middleware (heavy, often becomes a monolith itself)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Store-and-forward for DHL webhooks rather than synchronous processing",
      "gains": "Guaranteed 500ms SLA compliance, resilience to downstream processing failures, replay capability",
      "sacrifices": "Added latency between webhook receipt and domain event emission (typically <1s but non-zero), requires durable queue infrastructure",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Synchronous processing in webhook handler (risky — any downstream slowness violates SLA)", "In-memory queue (fast but not durable — lost on crash)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Outbox pattern for SAP batch rather than direct event-to-SFTP on timer",
      "gains": "Exactly-once delivery guarantee, crash recovery, clear audit trail of what was sent when",
      "sacrifices": "Extra database table and polling logic, slightly more complex than a simple cron job reading events",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Direct timer reading from event log (works if event log is durable, but tighter coupling to event store internals)", "SAP pulling from an API (SAP doesn't support this in the given constraint)"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Separate Webhook Ingress Gateway from DHL Integration Adapter",
      "gains": "Independent scaling, SLA isolation, security boundary separation, testability",
      "sacrifices": "Two components instead of one, network hop between them",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Single combined service (simpler deployment but conflates fast-ACK and slow-processing responsibilities)"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Adding new carriers (e.g., FedEx, UPS)",
      "evolution_path": "Create a new Carrier Integration Adapter implementing the same internal event interface. The core domain and other adapters remain untouched. The internal event bus handles fan-out naturally."
    },
    {
      "area": "Adding new event consumers",
      "evolution_path": "Any new system (e.g., a customer notification service, a billing system) subscribes to the internal event bus. Zero changes to publishers or existing consumers."
    },
    {
      "area": "Changing SAP integration cadence or protocol",
      "evolution_path": "The SAP Adapter is isolated behind its ACL. Switching from SFTP to SAP's REST API or changing from 15-minute batches to near-real-time requires changes only within the SAP Adapter."
    },
    {
      "area": "Analytics schema evolution",
      "evolution_path": "The Analytics Stream Publisher owns the external Kafka schema independently from the internal event schema. Schema registry with compatibility checks (backward/forward) enables safe evolution."
    },
    {
      "area": "Replacing the internal event bus technology",
      "evolution_path": "If the internal bus starts as an in-process mediator (e.g., MediatR) and later needs to become a distributed broker (e.g., RabbitMQ, internal Kafka), the adapters subscribe via an abstraction layer. The domain services publish through the same interface."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "The six canonical domain events (OrderPlaced through DeliveryFailed)",
      "reason": "These form the published language of the system. Changing their schema is a breaking change for all consumers (SAP Adapter, DHL Adapter, Analytics Publisher). This is intentional — the event schema should be versioned and evolved carefully with backward compatibility. Rigidity here forces discipline."
    },
    {
      "area": "Webhook 500ms SLA enforcement via store-and-forward",
      "reason": "The async ingestion pattern for DHL webhooks is non-negotiable given the 500ms constraint. Any attempt to add synchronous processing to the webhook handler will eventually violate the SLA under load."
    },
    {
      "area": "ACL boundaries per external system",
      "reason": "Each external system MUST have its own ACL. Sharing translation logic between adapters (e.g., a 'universal carrier adapter') creates coupling between independently evolving external contracts. Keep them separate even if there's initial code duplication."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "DHL webhook replay / duplicate delivery — DHL may resend webhooks if they don't receive a timely ACK, or network issues cause duplicates",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Implement idempotency at the Webhook Ingress Gateway using DHL's event ID as a deduplication key. Store processed event IDs in a fast lookup (Redis or DB unique constraint). The DHL Adapter must also be idempotent — applying the same status update twice should be a no-op."
    },
    {
      "risk": "SAP SFTP batch failure leaves a gap — if a 15-minute batch fails to upload, the next batch may not include the failed orders",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Outbox pattern with explicit acknowledgment. Orders in the outbox are only marked 'exported' after successful SFTP upload confirmation. Failed batches are retried on the next cycle. Dead letter after N failures with alerting."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Internal event bus becomes a single point of failure — if the bus goes down, all integrations halt",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Use a durable, replicated message broker (e.g., Kafka, RabbitMQ with mirrored queues) for the internal bus. If starting with an in-process bus, plan the migration path to a distributed broker before the system goes to production. Health checks and circuit breakers on all consumers."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Analytics Kafka producer backpressure — if System C's Kafka cluster is slow or unavailable, the Analytics Publisher's consumer lag grows unboundedly",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Implement bounded buffers with backpressure signaling. Monitor consumer lag. If Kafka is unavailable, the publisher pauses consumption from the internal bus (messages stay durably queued there) and resumes when Kafka recovers. Alert on lag thresholds."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Event schema drift between internal canonical events and external system expectations",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Enforce schema contracts with a schema registry for the Analytics Kafka topic. For SAP XML, maintain versioned XSD schemas in the repository. For DHL, pin API version and test against DHL's sandbox. Contract tests at each ACL boundary."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Webhook endpoint exposed to the public internet — DHL callbacks arrive over HTTPS but the endpoint is an attack surface",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "HMAC signature verification on every incoming webhook. IP allowlisting if DHL publishes their callback source IPs. Rate limiting at the gateway level. WAF in front of the webhook endpoint."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Implement in three phases. Phase 1: Stand up the Internal Event Bus (start with a durable broker — Kafka or RabbitMQ — don't start with in-memory if production use is near) and the core domain services emitting the six canonical events. Phase 2: Build the three ACL adapters in parallel since they are independent — SAP (outbox + SFTP scheduler), DHL (REST client + webhook ingress with store-and-forward queue), Analytics (Kafka producer with schema registry). Phase 3: Add observability — dead letter dashboard, consumer lag monitoring, SFTP upload audit log, end-to-end event tracing with correlation IDs. Each adapter should be independently deployable and testable. Use contract tests at every ACL boundary.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "src/domain/events/ — canonical event definitions (OrderPlaced.ts, OrderConfirmed.ts, ShipmentCreated.ts, DeliveryAttempted.ts, DeliveryCompleted.ts, DeliveryFailed.ts)",
      "src/domain/order/ — Order aggregate, OrderService",
      "src/domain/shipment/ — Shipment aggregate, ShipmentService",
      "src/infrastructure/event-bus/ — EventBus interface + broker implementation (KafkaEventBus or RabbitMQEventBus)",
      "src/integration/sap/ — SapAdapter, XmlTransformer, SftpClient, OutboxRepository, BatchScheduler",
      "src/integration/dhl/ — DhlAdapter, DhlApiClient, WebhookIngressController, WebhookQueue, StatusTranslator",
      "src/integration/analytics/ — AnalyticsStreamPublisher, AvroSerializer, SchemaRegistryClient",
      "src/infrastructure/dead-letter/ — DeadLetterStore, RetryScheduler",
      "src/infrastructure/observability/ — CorrelationIdMiddleware, EventTracer"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Anti-Corruption Layer at every external boundary. Store-and-forward for inbound webhooks. Outbox pattern for batched outbound. Event-driven fan-out from a single internal bus. Idempotent consumers everywhere. Correlation IDs threaded through all events for end-to-end tracing.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT process DHL webhooks synchronously in the HTTP handler — you will violate the 500ms SLA under load or when downstream systems are slow",
      "DO NOT let SAP's XML schema leak into your domain model — the ACL must fully translate between canonical events and SAP's format",
      "DO NOT share a single 'integration adapter' class for multiple external systems — each system evolves independently and coupling them creates a change amplifier",
      "DO NOT use an in-memory event bus for production — it is not durable, and a process restart loses events. Start with a real broker.",
      "DO NOT skip idempotency — DHL will send duplicate webhooks, SFTP uploads can be retried, Kafka consumers can reprocess. Every handler must be safe to call twice with the same input.",
      "DO NOT publish raw external payloads to the internal event bus — always translate to canonical domain events first. The bus is your domain's language, not DHL's or SAP's."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 88,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Event-driven backbone with internal bus is the clearly correct pattern for fan-out to three independent external systems",
      "Store-and-forward for webhook ingestion is the only reliable way to meet the 500ms SLA",
      "ACL per external system is well-established and unambiguous",
      "Outbox pattern for SAP batch integration is a natural fit for the 15-minute SFTP cadence"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Choice of internal event bus technology (Kafka vs RabbitMQ vs other) — depends on existing infrastructure, team expertise, and operational maturity which are not specified",
      "Exact SAP XML schema and SFTP directory conventions — requires SAP team coordination",
      "Whether DHL provides HMAC signatures on webhooks or uses a different verification mechanism — must confirm with DHL API docs"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The internal event bus will be a durable message broker, not an in-process mediator",
      "DHL webhooks arrive over HTTPS and include some form of request signature for verification",
      "SAP expects files deposited in a specific SFTP directory and polls for them (standard SAP integration pattern)",
      "The Analytics Platform can consume from a Kafka topic directly — no additional transformation gateway is required on their side",
      "The six domain events listed are the complete set — no additional events are needed for the three integrations",
      "The platform runs in an environment where Kafka (for analytics) is already available or can be provisioned"
    ]
  }
}

